<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06121224 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06121224 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  LESOTHO; MILITARY; GOVERNMENT; RESIGN  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The military government of the small mountain kingdom of Lesotho resignedtoday after troops surrounded the military leader's residence and carried outa bloodless coup.;    Maj. Gen. Justin Metsing Lekhanya, head of thesix-member ruling military council, read a statement on state-run RadioLesotho announcing the resignation of himself and his &quot;colleagues.&quot;  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  LESOTHO MILITARY GOVERNMENT RESIGNSTROOPS ARREST HEAD OF RULING COUNCIL DURINGBLOODLESS COUP  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     South Africa's Foreign Affairs Ministry said Col. E.P. Ramaeme, a member ofthe six-man military council, took over the leadership.;    Radio Lesothoreported Lekhanya, 54, had been arrested. Maseru, the capital, was reportedquiet.;    Lekhanya had pledged to return the country to civilian rule in1992.;    The South African Press Association reported an armored battalionsurrounded Lekhanya's residence at about 9 a.m. today, and soldiers took thegeneral to the radio station at gunpoint.;    &quot;It seems to me that the nationhas been complaining for some time over my leadership and the performance ofsome of my colleagues,&quot; said Lekhanya's announcement, broadcast in Sotho. &quot;I,therefore, announce my resignation and that of my colleagues.&quot;;    Maseruresidents said it appeared a salary dispute was a reason for the coup.;    Alarge segment of the military began striking Monday for higher wages, MikeTaole of the Christian Council of Lesotho told the press association. Today,he said, a military force surrounded Lekhanya's house and after several hoursof discussions among senior officers, the general went to the radio station.;   Raneo Khogang, editor of Radio Lesotho's news section, told the pressassociation a trembling Lekhanya arrived at the station under heavy militaryescort. He said the pre-recorded announcement was broadcast while Lekhanyalistened.;    Lesotho is a constitutional monarchy. A king is the head ofstate, but he has no executive power.;    Lekhanya seized power in a 1986 coupthat ousted an increasingly leftist authoritarian government that hadmaintained power through army support.;    The 1986 coup was staged afterSouth Africa imposed a blockade on Lesotho because of the government's supportfor the African National Congress.;    Lekhanya initially gave King MoshoeshoeII some executive authority, but fired most of the king's supporters inFebruary 1990 and told him to leave the country when Moshoeshoe refused toapprove the replacements.;    In October, Lekhanya invited Moshoeshoe toreturn from exile in London, but later rescinded the invitation because ofwhat he called unreasonable demands by the king, including dissolution of thegovernment. He then stripped Moshoeshoe of his title and power.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Johannesburg, South Africa  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910430  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  7A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  401  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday April 30, 199100121224,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>